        "content": "<p>Hello, novice user here. Is there any quick theorem for a | b -&gt; a | c -&gt; forall w x, a | w<em>b + x</em>c? (i.e., divisibility of linear combinations)</p>",
        "id": 214590807,
        "sender_full_name": "Meyer Zinn",
        "timestamp": 1603727003
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That looks to me like an easy consequence of two theorems which are probably there: <code>a | b -&gt; a | w*b</code> and <code>a | b -&gt; a | c -&gt; a | (b+c)</code></p>",
        "id": 214591111,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1603727102
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess not directly, but with a combo of <code>dvd_add</code> and <code>dvd_mul_(left|right)</code> you should be able to get there.</p>",
        "id": 214591166,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1603727122
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(let us know if we've said enough)</p>",
        "id": 214591425,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1603727200
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You probably want <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/dvd_mul_of_dvd_left\">docs#dvd_mul_of_dvd_left</a> (as opposed to <code>dvd_mul_left</code>)</p>",
        "id": 214591617,
